        Architectural stone fireplace solutions
      </a>

    </div>

  </div>

</section>


<section class="materials-faq">

  <div class="container">

    <h2>
      FAQ
    </h2>

    <p class="faq-intro">
      Answers to common questions about natural stone materials,
      applications and maintenance.
    </p>

    <div class="faq-list">

      <details class="faq-item">

        <summary>
          What is the best stone for bathroom sinks?
        </summary>

        <p>
          Marble, travertine and onyx are popular choices for luxury
          bathroom sinks. The best option depends on the desired style,
          maintenance requirements and project budget.
        </p>

      </details>

      <details class="faq-item">

        <summary>
          Is quartzite more durable than marble?
        </summary>

        <p>
          Yes. Quartzite is generally harder and more resistant to
          scratches and etching than marble, making it suitable for
          high-use surfaces.
        </p>

      </details>

      <details class="faq-item">

        <summary>
          Does travertine require sealing?
        </summary>

        <p>
          Yes. Travertine is a porous natural stone and should be sealed
          periodically to help protect against moisture and staining.
        </p>

      </details>

      <details class="faq-item">

        <summary>
          What is the most durable natural stone?
        </summary>

        <p>
          Granite and quartzite are among the most durable natural stones,
          offering excellent strength and long-term performance.
        </p>

      </details>

      <details class="faq-item">

        <summary>
          Can natural stone be customized?
        </summary>

        <p>
          Yes. Natural stone can be fabricated into custom sinks, tables,
          bathtubs, fireplace surrounds and architectural elements in a
          wide range of dimensions and finishes.
        </p>

      </details>

      <details class="faq-item">

        <summary>
          Which stone is best for luxury furniture?
        </summary>

        <p>
          Marble, travertine, onyx and premium quartzites are frequently
          selected for luxury furniture because of their unique patterns
          and architectural appeal.
        </p>

      </details>

    </div>

  </div>

</section>
